    "## Discusison and Conclusion\n",
    "\n",
    "Our team has examined the relationship between night sleep duration and academic performance for college freshmen. We analyzed whether average sleep time was associated with end-of-semester GPA while accounting for prior academic performance and demographic factors. According to our explanatory analyses,the majority of students slept between 350 and 450 minutes each night, with an average of 400 minutes (roughly 6.7 hours). Students with higher GPAs tended to have slightly longer average sleep durations comparing sleep duration across GPA categories. However, the differences between groups were small and there was a significant overlap across GPA categories.\n\n",

    "The results show that there is a slight positive correlation between sleep duration and academic performance. Based on the scatterplots and correlation analysis, a slight positive relationship between total sleep time and semester GPA has shown, which means students who slept longer tended to have slightly higher GPAs on average. Additionally, prior cumulative GPA demonstrated a significantly stronger correlation with semester GPA, which is to be expected given that prior academic performance is frequently a reliable indicator of future results. These results show that although sleep patterns may help students succeed academically, they are just one of many variables affecting their performance.\n\n",

    "Another aspect we explored was sleep regularity. We found a moderate negative correlation between irregular sleep schedules and GPA by using the bedtime variability measure. Students with more irregular sleep patterns performed a little worse academically compared to students who had more regular sleep schedules. Despite the fact that this trend was not very strong, it suggests that students might benefit from maintaining a consistent sleeping pattern. Overall, the analyses demonstrate that both sleep duration and consistency may have an impact on academic outcomes.\n\n",

    "As we went through this study, there are several limitations that should be considered when interpreting the results. First, as the dataset only includes students who agreed to wear a Fitbit device, selection bias may be generated. Students who volunteer for these types of studies may be more organized or health-conscious than the average student, which could be a factor that influences sleep patterns and academic performance. Second, even though Fitbit devices offer objective sleep measurements, they sometimes incorrectly interpret quiet wakefulness periods as sleep or fail to record data due to technical problems. Lastly, since this study relies on observational data, we are unable to draw the conclusion that sleep improves academic performance. Both sleep and GPA may be impacted by additional variables like stress levels, time management abilities, mental health, and study habits.\n\n",

    "We expect that future research might expand on this work if we could observe sleep patterns over longer time periods and across a wider range of universities. Understanding how changes in sleeping patterns impact academic performance may be improved by longitudinal data that tracks students over several semesters. To give a more comprehensive picture of student success, other factors like stress levels, workload, and lifestyle choices could also be included. Overall, this study shows that getting enough sleep on a regular basis may improve academic performances, but it is probably just one aspect of a much wider range of factors that influence students' performance.\n\n"
